the enormous harm that has been done physically, emotionally, and spiritually by that separation.The evidence of harm is everywhere: crippled and dysfunctional families, rampant drug and alcohol abuse, disproportionately high incidences of arrest and incarceration, and alarming health and mortality statistics, some of which may be traced to diet and lifestyle, which themselves are traceable to the separation from ‘āina. This volume articulates the critical needs that call the Kanaka back to the ‘āina and invites the reader to remember the thousands of years that our ancestors walked, named, and planted the land and were themselves planted in it.Contributors: Carlos Andrade, Kamana Beamer, April Drexel, Dana Nāone Hall, Neil Hannahs, Lia O’Neill Keawe, Jamaica Osorio, No‘eau Peralto, Kekailoa Perry, and Kaiwipuni Lipe with Lilikalā Kame‘eleihiwa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican poetryzHawaii. 0aHawaiiansxLand tenure. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAndrade, Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndrade, Carlos.1 aBeamer, Kamanamaikalani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeamer, Kamanamaikalani.1 aHall, Dana Naone.1 aHall, Dana Nāone, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHannahs, Neil J.1 aHannahs, Neil J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeawe, Lia O’Neill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipe, Kaiwipuni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipe, Kaiwipunikauikawēkiu.1 aOsorio, Jamaica Heolimeleikalani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOsorio, Jamaica Heolimeleikalani.1 aOsorio, Jonathan Kay Kamakawiwo‘ole, eeditor.4edt